		{"id":"7708e686bc1ca9a0","type":"text","text":"`RAID 6` --> `Striping with dual parity`\n1. `Minimum disk required is 4`\n\t1. `2 for parity`\n\t2. `2 for striping or say storage disk`\n\n***Advantage*** : `It is more secure because 2 disk is used for parity so even one parity disk fails or one striping disk our data is not going to loose because of second parity disk`\n\n***Disadvantage*** : `Write operation is 20% slower than RAID 5 because of extra calculation on parity disk`\n\n* `Striping` --> Striping means data breaks or spilt and store in different disk.","x":-577,"y":-300,"width":797,"height":700,"color":"1"},
		{"id":"95793e2766137e3b","type":"text","text":"**Creating `RAID 6`**\n\n1. suppose we have `6 disc` and we haven't make partition this time \n\t1. `/dev/sda`\n\t2. `/dev/sdb`\n\t3. `/dev/sdc`\n\t4. `/dev/sdd`\n\t5. `/dev/sde`\n\t6. `/dev/sdf`\n2. `mdadm --create /dev/md0 -l 6 -n 4 /dev/sda /dev/sdb /dev/sdc /dev/sdd` there disks are used to make `RAID 6`\n\t1. `-l 6` meaning `RAID level 6`\n\t2. `-n 4` four disk is being used\n3. `mdadm --detail /dev/md0` give complete information about `RAID /dev/md0`\n4. `cat /proc/mdstat` give `RAID /dev/md0` information\n5. `mkfs.xfs /dev/md0`\n6. `mkdir /raid6`\n7. `mount /dev/md0 /raid6`\n8. `df -hT`\n9. `cd /raid6`\n10. `touch file{1..100}.txt`\n\n***\n\n**How to fail or fault the disk in `RAID`\n\n1. `mdadm /dev/md0 -f /dev/sda`\n\t1. here we are failing disk `/dev/sda`\n\t2. `cat /proc/mdstat` it will show `F` in front of `sda disk` meaning faulty disk\n2. `mdadm /dev/md0 -f /dev/sdb`\n\t1. here we are failing disk `/dev/sdb`\n\t2. `cat /proc/mdstat` it will show `F` in front of `sdb disk` meaning faulty disk\n3. `mdadm --detail /dev/md0` it will show complete information like faulty disk, how many used to make `RAID` also `RAID level` which is `6` etc.\n\n***\n\n**How to replace faulty disk**\n1. first unmount the disk\n\t1. `umount /raid6`\n2. `mdadm /dev/md0 -r /dev/sda` \n\t1. `-r` remove \n3. `mdadm /dev/md0 -r /dev/sdb`\n4. `mdadm /dev/md0 -a /dev/sde` here adding new disk\n5. `mdadm /dev/md0 -a /dev/sdf` here adding another new disk because we `failed 2 disk` so we are replacing it by `2 new disk`\n6. `cat /proc/mdstat` it will show `recover data`\n7. `mdadm -D /dev/md0`\n\t1. `-D` or `--detail` is same thing\n8. `mount /dev/md0 /raid6`\n9. `cd /raid6`\n10. `ll` you will see our data. even though one disk is failed still our data has not lost\n","x":260,"y":-300,"width":1060,"height":1340,"color":"1"},
